TikTok Hides Uncomfortable Videos from Users
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under the age of 18.
Imagine China / Reuters
China’s TikTok social network is censoring videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibet’s independence, or the banned religious group Falun Gong, The Guardian reports.
The documents, which appeared at the publication, say that the owner of TikTok (ByteDance company) with the help of the app promotes the goals of China’s foreign policy abroad.
The main part of the violations concerning China’s policy falls under the “inflammation of hatred”.
In each case, TikTok places unpleasant posts in a context that is appropriate under the general rules so that the actions of the social network do not look censored.
For example, the ban on criticism of China’s socialist system falls under the general ban “criticism or attacks on the policies and social rules of any country, such as constitutional monarchy, parliamentary system, etc.”
The ban on the mention of incidents in Tiananmen Square or the genocide in Cambodia falls under the “story of China or other countries”.
The document also lists the banned names of twenty "foreign presidents or state officials", including the North Korean documentaries Kim Jong-un, Kim Il-sen, and Kim Jong-un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, U.S. Presidents Donald Trump, Yajong Trump, and Bar.
The prohibited material is divided into two categories, as stated in the document.
Publications from the first category are removed by the social network administrators and may result in the user being blocked.
Not too strict violations fall into the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited to TikTok algorithms.
ByteDance representatives told The Guardian that these rules were outdated and no longer applied: “We are now using a localized approach to moderation, as well as attracting independent local experts.”
Russian users of TikTok do not have specific restrictions on publication, says co-founder of the “Producer Center” Rustem Bogdanov.
“Producer Center” is one of the Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All the advertising materials of the bloggers "Producer Center" agree with the representatives of the social network, but the user materials can be placed without consent, Bogdanov reports.
Asked if TikTok could comment on the policy or Putin, Bogdanov replied affirmatively and said that he had seen such publications.
Bogdanov agrees with the founder of the agency Our Didgital Roman Zaripov: “The basic rules for users of TikTok are listed in the user agreement: it is not possible to post shocking content, discriminative statements and so on.”
But under these rules you can bring down any content that moderators don’t like, notes Zaripov.
Zaripova Agency is another Russian partner TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under the age of 18.
Under the user agreement, TikTok can only be used by persons over 13 years of age.
The administrators of the social network check their age with artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes the face and determines how many years a person looks, says Bogdanov.
If the neural network decides that the user is younger, its account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of WeWork coworking.
